'''Namerikawa no Nebuta Nagashi''' (滑川のネブタ流し) is a [[:en:Festival of fire|Fire festival]] held annually on July 31st at Nakagawara Beach (locally known as Wada no Hama) in [[:en:Namerikawa, Toyama|Namerikawa, Toyama]], [[:en:Toyama Prefecture|Toyama Prefecture]]. It involves floating blazing {{ill|torches|ja|松明|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/torches|qq=}} into the sea to pray for protection from misfortune, good health, and to ward off sleepiness. It is considered the southernmost occurrence of the {{ill|nebuta|ja|ねぶた|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/nebuta|qq=}} festival along the Sea of Japan and has been designated as an {{ill|Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|ja|重要無形民俗文化財|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property|qq=}} of Japan.
== Overview == The torches are constructed on wooden bases, standing approximately 4 to 6 meters tall, with a base diameter of 0.7 to 0.8 meters and a top diameter of 0.3 to 0.4 meters. The torches are wrapped with [[:en:Straw|straw]], {{ill|mats|ja|むしろ|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/mats|qq=}}, and bound with rough ropes. Decorative elements include effigies ([[:en:Katashiro|hitogata]]), made from items such as {{ill|eggplants|ja|茄子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/eggplants|qq=}} or {{ill|cucumbers|ja|胡瓜|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/cucumbers|qq=}} adorned with facial features, dressed in paper clothing, paper cutouts, or {{ill|tanzaku|ja|短冊|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tanzaku|qq=}} inscribed with prayers.
Around 2:00 PM, a purification ritual ([[:en:Ōharae-shiki|Ōharae]]) is performed at the {{ill|Ichihara Shrine|ja|櫟原神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ichihara Shrine|qq=}} purification site. At approximately 5:00 PM, participants carry the torches to Wada no Hama, chanting "Nebuta nagasare, asa okyare" (meaning "Drive away the nebuta and wake up in the morning"). After arriving at the beach, the torches are ignited at around 6:30 PM. Both children and adults enter the sea with the torches, ensuring they burn out completely. It is said that "nebuta" symbolizes sleepiness, and from July 31st onward, daytime napping is forbidden according to tradition.
The festival was designated as a national Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property on December 21, 1999, and in 2006 it was selected as one of the "100 Cultural Properties of Toyama" (Festivals Category:Pages with redlinks to fill]]
[[Category) by the Toyama Prefecture Board of Education.
== Towns Participating in Nebuta Nagashi == Historically, towns along Wada no Hama participated in the festival. Today, it is conducted by four preservation groups from Nakagawara and Tokiwamachi (1st, 2nd, and 3rd Districts), along with contributions from Azumamachi, the {{ill|Namerikawa Junior Chamber|ja|日本青年会議所|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Namerikawa Junior Chamber|qq=}}, {{ill|Namerikawa Municipal Jike Elementary School|ja|滑川市立寺家小学校|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Namerikawa Municipal Jike Elementary School|qq=}}, and others. For example: - In 2010, 11 nebuta floats were launched. - In 2012, Namerikawa Higashi District Community Center joined, increasing the count to 12.<ref>{{Cite news|title=祈りの炎 海染める 滑川ネブタ流し|newspaper=北日本新聞|date=2012-08-01}}</ref> - In 2017, Namerikawa City Hall joined, and 11 floats were launched.<ref>{{Cite news|title=祈りの炎 赤々と 滑川ネブタ流し|newspaper=北日本新聞|date=2017-08-01}}</ref> - In 2018, Namerikawa Nishi District Community Center participated for the first time.<ref>{{Cite news|title=祈りの炎 海染める 滑川ネブタ流し|newspaper=北日本新聞|date=2018-08-01}}</ref>
=== Current Participants === - Nakagawara, Tokiwamachi (1st, 2nd, and 3rd Districts), Azumamachi, Namerikawa Junior Chamber, Jike Elementary School, Namerikawa Higashi District Community Center, Namerikawa Nishi District Community Center, Namerikawa City Hall
=== Former Participants === - Shinmeicho, Jikemachi, Mihomachi, Kamiyamachi, Sawamachi, Tanakamachi, Kajimamachi (2nd and 3rd Districts), Ryokemachi, Takatsukimachi East, Takatsukimachi West
